# Plan: Add JWT Authentication to Express API

## Context

The Express API has fully functional CRUD routes for posts and comments but no authentication layer. Write operations accept any `userId` from the request body (defaulting to 1), meaning anyone can create, modify, or delete any resource. The goal is to add JWT-based registration/login, protect all write endpoints, and enforce ownership so only the resource creator can mutate or delete it. All existing tests (`posts.test.ts`, `comments.test.ts`) and the pre-written `auth.test.ts` must pass.

---

## Files to Create

### 1. `src/middleware/auth.ts` _(new)_

Exports the `authenticate` middleware and the shared `JWT_SECRET` constant. Also performs the Express `Request` type augmentation so `req.user` is typed throughout the codebase.

```ts
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { JwtPayload } from "../types.js";

declare global {
  namespace Express {
    interface Request {
      user?: JwtPayload;
    }
  }
}

export const JWT_SECRET = "super-secret-key";

export function authenticate(
  req: Request,
  res: Response,
  next: NextFunction
): void {
  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !authHeader.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });
    return;
  }
  const token = authHeader.slice(7);
  try {
    const payload = jwt.verify(token, JWT_SECRET) as JwtPayload;
    req.user = payload;
    next();
  } catch {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid or expired token" });
  }
}
```

> `declare global` works here because the file has `import` statements, making it a TypeScript module rather than a script.

---

### 2. `src/routes/auth.ts` _(new)_

Handles `POST /auth/register` and `POST /auth/login`. Passwords are stored and compared as plaintext (no bcrypt) because the tests register then immediately log in with the same string.

```ts
import { Router } from "express";
import jwt from "jsonwebtoken";
import { users, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { JwtPayload } from "../types.js";
import { JWT_SECRET } from "../middleware/auth.js";

const router = Router();

// POST /auth/register → 201 { token, user (no password) }
router.post("/register", (req, res) => {
  const { username, email, password } = req.body;
  if (!username || !email || !password) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "username, email, and password are required" });
    return;
  }
  if (users.find((u) => u.username === username)) {
    res.status(409).json({ error: "Username already taken" });
    return;
  }
  const newUser = { id: nextId(users), username, email, password };
  users.push(newUser);
  const payload: JwtPayload = { userId: newUser.id, username: newUser.username };
  const token = jwt.sign(payload, JWT_SECRET);
  const { password: _pw, ...userWithoutPassword } = newUser;
  res.status(201).json({ token, user: userWithoutPassword });
});

// POST /auth/login → 200 { token }
router.post("/login", (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;
  const user = users.find((u) => u.username === username);
  if (!user || user.password !== password) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid credentials" });
    return;
  }
  const payload: JwtPayload = { userId: user.id, username: user.username };
  const token = jwt.sign(payload, JWT_SECRET);
  res.status(200).json({ token });
});

export { router as authRouter };
```

